1
00:02:58,405 --> 00:03:00,118
Daddy William!

2
00:03:01,212 --> 00:03:02,719
Daddy William!

3
00:03:03,006 --> 00:03:05,832
Don't let them take you away!

4
00:03:07,510 --> 00:03:10,409
Momma needs you, we need you.

5
00:03:11,303 --> 00:03:12,819
Now go home, child.

6
00:03:13,405 --> 00:03:15,107
Ain't nothing you can do.

7
00:03:15,787 --> 00:03:17,603
I belong to Legree now.

8
00:03:18,597 --> 00:03:20,506
When you coming home?

9
00:03:20,905 --> 00:03:22,209
Never, child!

10
00:03:22,897 --> 00:03:24,322
Now you go home,

11
00:03:25,897 --> 00:03:27,524
tell your mama I love her,

12
00:03:28,197 --> 00:03:29,408
and you, too.

13
00:03:30,401 --> 00:03:31,607
Now get!

14
00:03:36,596 --> 00:03:39,411
Now that's a fine young filly.

15
00:03:39,917 --> 00:03:41,102
Let her be.

16
00:03:41,197 --> 00:03:43,402
Now why should I do that, boy?

17
00:03:44,701 --> 00:03:46,018
Run, child!

18
00:03:55,196 --> 00:03:57,292
Not if you wanna live, nigger.

19
00:03:57,899 --> 00:03:59,901
Daddy!

20
00:04:05,399 --> 00:04:06,876
Daddy!

21
00:04:06,927 --> 00:04:09,813
Hey, boy, I'm gonna fuck your daughter!

22
00:04:09,907 --> 00:04:12,610
Don't let them hurt me!

23
00:04:13,200 --> 00:04:14,703
He gets all the fun.

24
00:04:15,403 --> 00:04:16,817
Let's move them out.

25
00:04:16,997 --> 00:04:18,430
He can catch up later.

26
00:04:19,090 --> 00:04:20,111
Come on, nigger.

27
00:04:20,192 --> 00:04:22,723
Hey, get up there.
Move.

28
00:04:28,401 --> 00:04:29,508
Move!

29
00:04:56,396 --> 00:04:57,505
No!

30
00:06:43,606 --> 00:06:45,843
My land, childrens,
ain't they any other place

31
00:06:45,894 --> 00:06:48,005
for y'all to sit except on the stairs?

32
00:06:48,075 --> 00:06:49,114
Morning, Eliza.

33
00:06:49,169 --> 00:06:50,716
I see you're busy already.

34
00:06:50,767 --> 00:06:52,844
Master going out?
- These aren't Master Shelby's

35
00:06:52,895 --> 00:06:54,216
boots, they belong to the guest.

36
00:06:54,278 --> 00:06:56,621
Guest?
Ain't nobody told me about no guest,

37
00:06:56,672 --> 00:06:58,439
that's for sure certain, and Mr. Shelby

38
00:06:58,490 --> 00:07:00,121
always tells me when they's company.

39
00:07:00,176 --> 00:07:01,817
Well, his boots are here.

40
00:07:09,095 --> 00:07:11,224
May I come in, sir?
- Yes.

41
00:07:17,604 --> 00:07:19,712
I brought your boots, sir.

42
00:07:28,607 --> 00:07:29,718
All right.

43
00:07:32,006 --> 00:07:33,414
Help me on with them.

44
00:07:37,601 --> 00:07:38,816
What's your name?

45
00:07:38,890 --> 00:07:40,202
Eliza, sir.

46
00:07:42,698 --> 00:07:45,423
You've done a
good job on them, Eliza.

47
00:07:45,597 --> 00:07:46,808
Thank you, sir.

48
00:07:47,714 --> 00:07:49,800
Are you always so shy?

49
00:07:51,706 --> 00:07:53,208
Is anything wrong?

50
00:07:53,406 --> 00:07:54,526
No, sir.

51
00:07:55,707 --> 00:07:57,317
You have a man, Eliza?

52
00:07:57,414 --> 00:07:58,604
Oh, yes, sir.

53
00:07:58,689 --> 00:08:00,292
I should think so.

54
00:08:00,604 --> 00:08:02,378
He's a lucky man, you're very pretty.

55
00:08:02,429 --> 00:08:04,226
I suppose he'd like to marry you.

56
00:08:04,300 --> 00:08:06,015
We are married, sir.

57
00:08:06,101 --> 00:08:07,913
That's nice.
- Only I don't live with him.

58
00:08:08,001 --> 00:08:09,814
Our neighbor's his master.

59
00:08:10,010 --> 00:08:11,620
He's hired at the hemp mill.

60
00:08:11,800 --> 00:08:13,916
So he works for old Mr. Wilson?

61
00:08:15,202 --> 00:08:16,407
What's his name?

62
00:08:16,488 --> 00:08:18,315
Harris, sir, Jim Harris.

63
00:08:18,501 --> 00:08:20,003
Do you know him?

64
00:08:20,889 --> 00:08:21,889
No.

65
00:08:23,304 --> 00:08:24,917
Now can I go, please?

66
00:08:40,004 --> 00:08:41,807
You're very pretty, Eliza.

67
00:08:42,606 --> 00:08:45,216
How'd you like me to buy
you and take you home?

68
00:08:52,099 --> 00:08:53,618
Are you afraid of me?

69
00:08:56,809 --> 00:08:58,017
No, sir.

70
00:08:59,007 --> 00:09:00,724
Or of the South, perhaps.

71
00:09:01,095 --> 00:09:02,513
It's nice down there.

72
00:09:03,005 --> 00:09:05,524
But I'm very
happy right here, sir.

73
00:09:06,708 --> 00:09:08,113
Come back here later.

74
00:09:35,898 --> 00:09:37,211
I won't do it.

75
00:09:38,110 --> 00:09:40,726
Annie can just bring his water up to him.

76
00:09:40,895 --> 00:09:42,605
I'm not going up there.

77
00:09:42,906 --> 00:09:45,068
I'd rather throw myself in the river.

78
00:09:45,119 --> 00:09:46,777
Child, you supposed to be a Christian.

79
00:09:46,828 --> 00:09:47,980
Stop talking like that.

80
00:09:48,031 --> 00:09:49,668
They want us all to be good Christians,

81
00:09:49,719 --> 00:09:52,418
but they talk about it
one way and do us another.

82
00:09:52,469 --> 00:09:53,989
What's got into you, Eliza, honey?

83
00:09:54,040 --> 00:09:57,219
You look like you seen the ole
devil himself this morning.

84
00:09:57,592 --> 00:10:00,203
I never gave thought to
what the devil looks like,

85
00:10:00,406 --> 00:10:03,115
but I bet he looks a
powerful lot like him.

86
00:10:08,606 --> 00:10:10,512
You wanna see me, Mr. Morrison?

87
00:10:10,607 --> 00:10:12,536
You think I rode 10
miles for the fun of it?

88
00:10:12,587 --> 00:10:13,809
Where's Harris?

89
00:10:14,805 --> 00:10:16,614
What do you want with him?

90
00:10:16,903 --> 00:10:18,094
Is it all right with you, Wilson,

91
00:10:18,145 --> 00:10:19,200
if I sell my own slave?

92
00:10:19,294 --> 00:10:20,934
Does it have to be Harris?

93
00:10:20,985 --> 00:10:23,112
He's the best man I hired from you.

94
00:10:23,201 --> 00:10:25,505
I know what I'm doing,
Wilson, so don't butt in.

95
00:10:25,590 --> 00:10:28,313
But you'll want to see this
machine he built over here.

96
00:10:28,391 --> 00:10:29,608
He invented it himself.

97
00:10:29,659 --> 00:10:30,985
It does the work of six slaves.

98
00:10:31,036 --> 00:10:33,301
I don't know anything about machines
and I don't wanna.

99
00:10:33,396 --> 00:10:35,512
I'd rather use slaves,
they don't get rusty.

100
00:10:38,801 --> 00:10:40,119
That's all I need, ain't it,

101
00:10:40,170 --> 00:10:42,114
for some uppity nigger to
start inventing things?

102
00:10:42,176 --> 00:10:43,918
You keep your place, hear?

103
00:10:48,207 --> 00:10:50,512
You have no right
to do that, Mr. Morrison.

104
00:10:50,598 --> 00:10:52,131
I didn't rent you any brains, Wilson,

105
00:10:52,182 --> 00:10:53,628
just a pair of arms.

106
00:10:53,699 --> 00:10:56,034
I asked for good
workers, and I got them.

107
00:10:56,097 --> 00:10:57,722
He's the best man I have.

108
00:10:57,800 --> 00:11:00,417
Don't take him away, I'll buy him myself.

109
00:11:00,902 --> 00:11:04,030
Legree's my friend, he
paid a good price for him.

110
00:11:04,202 --> 00:11:06,015
He'll teach him what it means to work.

111
00:11:06,070 --> 00:11:07,521
Go on, inventor.

112
00:11:09,700 --> 00:11:10,912
Get moving!

113
00:11:11,997 --> 00:11:14,607
Don't take him away
from me, Mr. Morrison.

114
00:11:14,693 --> 00:11:17,708
I'll pay more than you're
getting from Mr. Legree.

115
00:11:17,800 --> 00:11:20,427
Forget it, Wilson, he's going to Legree.

116
00:11:20,607 --> 00:11:23,120
I can do what I want with my own property.

117
00:11:24,004 --> 00:11:26,212
I'll pay you $1,000 for him.

118
00:11:26,306 --> 00:11:29,018
Nothing doing, I told you, he's sold.

119
00:11:31,199 --> 00:11:32,918
1,500, Mr. Morrison.

120
00:11:34,401 --> 00:11:35,714
2,000!

121
00:11:35,901 --> 00:11:37,903
You'll never see him again.

122
00:12:24,100 --> 00:12:25,015
Run!

123
00:12:25,116 --> 00:12:26,718
Tomorrow, there'll be a reward notice

124
00:12:26,769 --> 00:12:28,929
on every tree from here to Kentucky!

125
00:12:44,099 --> 00:12:46,411
Have you been comfortable
with us, Mr. Legree?

126
00:12:46,474 --> 00:12:48,716
Now that business is out
of the way, yes, ma'am.

127
00:12:48,802 --> 00:12:51,020
Where's your son?
What's his name again?

128
00:12:51,091 --> 00:12:52,011
George.

129
00:12:52,062 --> 00:12:53,210
Please?
- Oh, thank you.

130
00:12:53,261 --> 00:12:54,753
He knows I hate unpunctuality.

131
00:12:54,804 --> 00:12:56,550
He's probably with Uncle Tom.

132
00:12:56,601 --> 00:12:58,215
He can look at a watch,
can't he, wherever he is.

133
00:12:58,266 --> 00:13:00,425
Well, time's not
important when you're young.

134
00:13:00,480 --> 00:13:03,116
He'll be old enough
for college next year.

135
00:13:03,202 --> 00:13:06,398
College, that'll be
pretty expensive, won't it?

136
00:13:06,476 --> 00:13:08,600
Well, with a big,
beautiful estate like this,

137
00:13:08,651 --> 00:13:10,714
you can afford it, I guess, hmm?

138
00:13:10,797 --> 00:13:12,924
With plenty of hard work, Mr. Legree.

139
00:13:12,998 --> 00:13:14,601
How well I know, madam.

140
00:13:14,796 --> 00:13:17,710
I've a plantation of my own down river.

141
00:13:17,906 --> 00:13:19,011
Down river?

142
00:13:19,097 --> 00:13:20,206
Near Natchez, ma'am.

143
00:13:20,257 --> 00:13:22,714
1,000 acres of long staple cotton.

144
00:13:22,808 --> 00:13:24,658
That's the only crop you can make money on

145
00:13:24,709 --> 00:13:26,015
because of the climate.

146
00:13:26,073 --> 00:13:27,408
Swamp fever.

147
00:13:27,591 --> 00:13:29,214
We lose a lot of slaves.

148
00:13:29,503 --> 00:13:31,019
But that's life there.

149
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:40,146
Excuse us, please, for being late.
We were listening to the singing.

150
00:13:40,197 --> 00:13:42,611
I don't believe you've met
the children yet, Mr. Legree.

151
00:13:42,681 --> 00:13:44,253
This is our Virginia.

152
00:13:45,603 --> 00:13:47,765
The reports didn't do
you justice, young lady.

153
00:13:47,816 --> 00:13:48,822
How do you do?

154
00:13:49,708 --> 00:13:51,408
May I offer my congratulations?

155
00:13:51,466 --> 00:13:52,712
How do you do, sir?

156
00:13:59,901 --> 00:14:01,810
Did you enjoy the spirituals?

157
00:14:02,008 --> 00:14:03,505
Yes, it was just lovely.

158
00:14:03,710 --> 00:14:05,017
They like to sing.

159
00:14:05,204 --> 00:14:07,714
Good thing, too, helps my business.

160
00:14:07,765 --> 00:14:09,677
It helps them work harder, is that it?

161
00:14:09,728 --> 00:14:12,517
Naturally there's more
profit in a happy nigger.

162
00:14:12,697 --> 00:14:16,497
For instance, take this case
I heard of the other day.

163
00:14:17,302 --> 00:14:19,755
There was this man, trader I know,

164
00:14:19,806 --> 00:14:21,516
bought a woman with a child,

165
00:14:21,603 --> 00:14:23,342
but he didn't have any use for the baby,

166
00:14:23,393 --> 00:14:24,625
so he sold it.

167
00:14:24,907 --> 00:14:26,314
Stupid thing to do.

168
00:14:26,391 --> 00:14:29,111
The mother killed herself.

169
00:14:29,310 --> 00:14:31,493
$1,000 wasted through mismanagement.

170
00:14:31,544 --> 00:14:34,626
The baby always goes with his
mother, that's what I say.

171
00:14:34,710 --> 00:14:36,509
It's just awful, isn't it?

172
00:14:36,603 --> 00:14:38,017
What can you do?

173
00:14:38,111 --> 00:14:40,208
The man had a law on his side.

174
00:14:40,302 --> 00:14:42,614
Laws like that should be abolished.

175
00:14:43,001 --> 00:14:44,579
You planning to be a lawyer, boy?

176
00:14:44,630 --> 00:14:46,223
I haven't decided on a career.

177
00:14:46,301 --> 00:14:48,715
I do know what I don't wanna be, however.

178
00:14:49,396 --> 00:14:50,609
What's that, young fella?

179
00:14:50,705 --> 00:14:52,922
A slave trader, Mr. Legree.
- George!

180
00:14:53,203 --> 00:14:54,665
A slave trader has to earn his living,

181
00:14:54,716 --> 00:14:56,125
just like everybody else.

182
00:14:56,894 --> 00:14:58,519
Aren't there other ways?

183
00:14:58,699 --> 00:15:00,121
I guess that depends.

184
00:15:01,298 --> 00:15:04,625
You're young, you're nice and gentle.

185
00:15:04,703 --> 00:15:06,719
So, for you, life should
be easy and beautiful,

186
00:15:06,770 --> 00:15:07,820
like yourself.

187
00:15:07,871 --> 00:15:09,273
As his life is ugly.

188
00:15:09,324 --> 00:15:10,521
George, how dare you.

189
00:15:10,573 --> 00:15:12,019
Apologize, do you hear?

190
00:15:18,016 --> 00:15:20,703
I'm sorry, Father, but I
will not apologize to him.

191
00:15:20,754 --> 00:15:21,758
George.

192
00:15:21,852 --> 00:15:23,680
Come back at once!
- Go after him, dear.

193
00:15:23,731 --> 00:15:24,548
Do you think I should?

194
00:15:24,599 --> 00:15:26,508
Certainly, my child, go ahead.

195
00:15:46,498 --> 00:15:50,335
Going away to college
might do him some good.

196
00:15:55,494 --> 00:15:56,595
Nice evening.

197
00:15:58,299 --> 00:16:00,414
Well, I won't stay any longer.

198
00:16:08,201 --> 00:16:11,408
Master, made him my master.

199
00:16:12,201 --> 00:16:14,124
What right does he have to own me?

200
00:16:14,697 --> 00:16:16,502
I'm a man just like he is.

201
00:16:18,600 --> 00:16:22,112
I'm not some kind of
a machine or an animal

202
00:16:22,200 --> 00:16:24,307
to be bought and abused and sold.

203
00:16:24,401 --> 00:16:25,729
I'll never be an animal again.

204
00:16:25,780 --> 00:16:26,510
What will you do?

205
00:16:26,561 --> 00:16:28,807
I don't know, go to Canada.

206
00:16:30,705 --> 00:16:32,315
They're good people there.

207
00:16:32,408 --> 00:16:34,127
No slaves, only freemen.

208
00:16:36,397 --> 00:16:38,006
I'll make lots of dollars,

209
00:16:38,084 --> 00:16:40,615
I'll make thousands and
thousands of dollars.

210
00:16:40,700 --> 00:16:42,600
I'll buy you both back.

211
00:16:42,701 --> 00:16:44,705
Yes, you and the baby, too.

212
00:16:45,006 --> 00:16:46,605
Be careful, Harris, you're hurt,

213
00:16:46,701 --> 00:16:48,932
and it's so cold and the river's frozen.

214
00:16:48,997 --> 00:16:50,412
Don't worry about me.

215
00:16:50,710 --> 00:16:52,323
I'll come back for you.

216
00:17:01,096 --> 00:17:02,417
I'll be all right.

217
00:17:03,112 --> 00:17:04,419
Take care of yourself.
- I have to go now,

218
00:17:04,470 --> 00:17:06,909
I have to run before
Morrison gets after me.

219
00:17:07,799 --> 00:17:09,823
I'll wait for you forever.

220
00:17:10,603 --> 00:17:12,010
Forever.

221
00:17:36,290 --> 00:17:39,014
No, Mr. Shelby
wouldn't say that.

222
00:17:41,001 --> 00:17:42,517
Shelby wouldn't do that.

223
00:17:42,568 --> 00:17:44,619
They said they wouldn't do that.

224
00:17:44,798 --> 00:17:47,501
What y'all hanging 'round for?
Get to work.

225
00:17:47,796 --> 00:17:50,208
There's a bad man with a scar
hanging around the place.

226
00:17:50,310 --> 00:17:52,509
That's Mr. Legree, he's
a guest of the master.

227
00:17:52,560 --> 00:17:55,033
That's just it, Mr. Shelby's
gonna sell some of us.

228
00:17:55,084 --> 00:17:56,091
What you talking about?

229
00:17:56,142 --> 00:17:58,509
That fellow Sambo who come with him...
- There's Mr. Shelby.

230
00:17:58,798 --> 00:18:01,732
Morning, Mr. Shelby.

231
00:18:01,783 --> 00:18:03,923
I'd like to talk to
you alone for a minute, Tom.

232
00:18:03,974 --> 00:18:05,017
Yes, sir.

233
00:18:06,909 --> 00:18:08,525
All right, get to
work, everybody, go on.

234
00:18:08,576 --> 00:18:10,808
Go on, put your arms into it.

235
00:18:11,308 --> 00:18:13,920
That Sambo of Mr. Legree,
he's started a lot of talk

236
00:18:14,002 --> 00:18:16,015
about how you wanna sell some of us,

237
00:18:16,066 --> 00:18:17,507
and they've gone half-crazy.

238
00:18:17,558 --> 00:18:19,007
I beg of you, Tom,
please don't make things

239
00:18:19,058 --> 00:18:20,413
any harder for me than they are.

240
00:18:20,464 --> 00:18:22,405
Well, I'd never do that to you, sir.

241
00:18:22,456 --> 00:18:24,166
Why, ever since we were little boys,

242
00:18:24,217 --> 00:18:26,218
we been looking after one another.

243
00:18:26,272 --> 00:18:30,108
Tom, suppose that
this isn't just a rumor,

244
00:18:30,186 --> 00:18:33,925
that I've been obliged
to have sold some of you.

245
00:18:34,499 --> 00:18:38,608
Then, then I knowed it
must be hard times for sure.

246
00:18:38,659 --> 00:18:40,557
Why else would you be fixing to sell

247
00:18:40,608 --> 00:18:42,511
any of us off the plantation?

248
00:18:42,589 --> 00:18:44,413
I knowed lessen you had to,

249
00:18:44,464 --> 00:18:46,065
you wouldn't never do nothing like that.

250
00:18:46,116 --> 00:18:46,960
Where you going?

251
00:18:47,011 --> 00:18:48,604
I'm getting my other shirt.

252
00:18:48,655 --> 00:18:51,417
But, Tom, there's no
question of your going.

253
00:18:51,503 --> 00:18:54,011
Why, you're as much a part
of the Shelby plantation

254
00:18:54,104 --> 00:18:55,612
as I am myself.

255
00:18:56,097 --> 00:18:58,408
All us is part of the Shelby plantation,

256
00:18:58,459 --> 00:19:00,218
like one big ole family.

257
00:19:00,295 --> 00:19:03,409
Mr. Shelby, if you are gonna sell anyone,

258
00:19:03,706 --> 00:19:06,511
please, sir, I want you to sell me.

259
00:19:07,296 --> 00:19:09,127
It say here in the Bible,

260
00:19:10,202 --> 00:19:12,506
no one has greater love than this,

261
00:19:12,557 --> 00:19:14,616
to lay down his life for a friend.

262
00:19:15,499 --> 00:19:17,710
If you don't want me to do it for you,

263
00:19:17,804 --> 00:19:20,308
then I'll do it for Master George, sir.

264
00:19:20,359 --> 00:19:23,620
Don't listen to him, sir,
don't listen to what he says.

265
00:19:23,671 --> 00:19:25,870
Please, sir, don't let him go away.

266
00:19:25,921 --> 00:19:27,925
They ain't nothing about
going in the Bible.

267
00:19:27,976 --> 00:19:29,507
Know what it says there?

268
00:19:29,558 --> 00:19:32,308
Tom, stay where you at.
- The Bible don't say one word about that.

269
00:19:32,359 --> 00:19:34,421
Then put it in!

270
00:19:39,311 --> 00:19:40,819
What's the matter, George?

271
00:19:40,870 --> 00:19:42,030
I'm gonna horsewhip Legree.

272
00:19:42,081 --> 00:19:44,397
He's a guest, your
father will be disgraced.

273
00:19:44,448 --> 00:19:46,037
He's already disgraced himself.

274
00:19:46,088 --> 00:19:48,819
But I beg you, please,
don't start trouble.

275
00:19:48,870 --> 00:19:50,924
Virginia, it's not a
question of starting trouble.

276
00:19:50,975 --> 00:19:52,268
But I'm not gonna just be idle

277
00:19:52,319 --> 00:19:55,119
while something like this
is happening to our people.

278
00:19:58,804 --> 00:20:00,328
I must speak to George for a minute.

279
00:20:00,379 --> 00:20:02,030
Will you excuse us, Virginia?

280
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:05,414
Have we anything left
to talk about, sir?

281
00:20:06,000 --> 00:20:08,289
Yes, all the things I've
been keeping to myself

282
00:20:08,340 --> 00:20:10,219
in order to spare your mother and you.

283
00:20:10,398 --> 00:20:12,082
Does watching
our people being sold

284
00:20:12,133 --> 00:20:14,812
like a bunch of animals
spare our feelings?

285
00:20:14,863 --> 00:20:17,863
I've been doing everything I
possibly could to avoid this.

286
00:20:17,914 --> 00:20:20,066
I've borrowed money
from all of my friends,

287
00:20:20,117 --> 00:20:22,416
I've sold most of your mother's jewelry.

288
00:20:23,004 --> 00:20:25,414
In heaven's name, what else could I do?

289
00:20:26,008 --> 00:20:27,512
Stop being hypocritical.

290
00:20:27,563 --> 00:20:29,207
How many times have you said you despise

291
00:20:29,258 --> 00:20:31,316
slave traders like Simon Legree?

292
00:20:31,597 --> 00:20:34,425
You're talking of things
you're too young to understand.

293
00:20:35,005 --> 00:20:36,112
Too young?

294
00:20:36,206 --> 00:20:38,284
Isn't it odd how that's
always the argument

295
00:20:38,347 --> 00:20:39,440
when you know that I'm in the right?

296
00:20:39,491 --> 00:20:41,307
George, I will overlook
your lack of respect

297
00:20:41,358 --> 00:20:43,104
under the circumstances.

298
00:20:43,198 --> 00:20:44,964
I even understand how you feel.

299
00:20:45,015 --> 00:20:46,612
It affects you just as it does me.

300
00:20:46,698 --> 00:20:48,417
Those are the ones
who are affected by it,

301
00:20:48,468 --> 00:20:49,917
those people out there.

302
00:20:50,007 --> 00:20:51,511
Come here and look at them.

303
00:20:56,906 --> 00:20:59,222
Hey, man, go on, move.

304
00:20:59,409 --> 00:21:01,009
See what they're doing?

305
00:21:01,700 --> 00:21:03,702
They're lining them all up.

306
00:21:03,909 --> 00:21:05,160
They're being herded like animals.

307
00:21:05,211 --> 00:21:07,096
Unfortunately, he has the right
to choose the ones he wants.

308
00:21:07,147 --> 00:21:08,702
And if Uncle Tom is chosen?

309
00:21:08,753 --> 00:21:10,123
I've been talking to Uncle Tom.

310
00:21:10,174 --> 00:21:11,293
He has to be one of the
people who...

311
00:21:11,344 --> 00:21:12,514
The sheriff.

312
00:21:12,601 --> 00:21:14,617
I'm sure it'll serve its purpose.

313
00:21:16,300 --> 00:21:17,272
You're free, Eliza.

314
00:21:17,323 --> 00:21:19,717
I always felt like I was free
with you folks, Miss Shelby.

315
00:21:19,803 --> 00:21:21,301
That's not the way they do things

316
00:21:21,352 --> 00:21:23,020
in the world outside now, Eliza.

317
00:21:23,099 --> 00:21:24,963
And don't forget, for little Harry,

318
00:21:25,014 --> 00:21:27,107
this document I gave you is useless.

319
00:21:27,193 --> 00:21:29,008
You have to be very careful.

320
00:21:29,106 --> 00:21:31,407
He belongs to Mr. Legree
in the eyes of the law.

321
00:21:31,485 --> 00:21:34,105
You could be accused of
kidnapping your own child.

322
00:21:34,907 --> 00:21:36,413
I haven't much money.

323
00:21:36,898 --> 00:21:38,114
Here, Eliza.

324
00:21:38,200 --> 00:21:39,611
Here, here's $20.
- Oh, no.

325
00:21:39,676 --> 00:21:41,937
I saved every cent of
the money you gave me.

326
00:21:41,988 --> 00:21:43,406
I don't need anymore.
- Go on, take the money,

327
00:21:43,457 --> 00:21:46,222
Eliza, you're sure to need
it before you're through.

328
00:21:46,308 --> 00:21:49,215
Tell old Jim to harness the
fastest horse in the stable.

329
00:21:49,266 --> 00:21:50,808
Just leave him at the ferry.

330
00:21:50,859 --> 00:21:53,105
How can I ever thank you?

331
00:21:53,301 --> 00:21:56,105
Write me when you've
found your husband and you're safe.

332
00:21:56,199 --> 00:21:57,462
And now you better hurry up.

333
00:21:57,513 --> 00:21:59,931
Mr. Legree's a very dangerous man.

334
00:22:07,801 --> 00:22:10,004
Go on, get in the wagon.

335
00:22:11,504 --> 00:22:12,717
Sit here.

336
00:22:14,902 --> 00:22:16,018
Gimme your ankle.

337
00:22:21,303 --> 00:22:22,414
Number eight.

338
00:22:22,995 --> 00:22:24,413
Get in the wagon.

339
00:22:39,702 --> 00:22:40,717
Nine.

340
00:22:40,807 --> 00:22:41,811
Over here.

341
00:22:41,897 --> 00:22:43,303
Where's number 10?

342
00:22:43,894 --> 00:22:44,905
Get in.

343
00:22:44,991 --> 00:22:46,108
Who's that, sir?

344
00:22:46,202 --> 00:22:48,046
The child, the maid's little boy.

345
00:22:48,097 --> 00:22:49,513
What's her name, Eliza?

346
00:22:50,003 --> 00:22:51,325
We've been looking for them.

347
00:22:51,376 --> 00:22:53,604
Nobody's seen her or the boy, sir.

348
00:22:53,698 --> 00:22:55,116
Where's the child?

349
00:22:55,167 --> 00:22:57,311
Eliza and the child are both gone.

350
00:22:57,374 --> 00:22:59,710
We've looked over the whole plantation.

351
00:22:59,811 --> 00:23:01,053
Where have they gone?

352
00:23:01,104 --> 00:23:02,608
You could ask Mrs. Shelby.

353
00:23:02,659 --> 00:23:04,217
Eliza belongs to her.

354
00:23:10,202 --> 00:23:11,354
It's important.

355
00:23:11,405 --> 00:23:14,324
I don't understand
how you can ask me to.

356
00:23:14,702 --> 00:23:17,412
I was under the impression
I was dealing with a gentleman.

357
00:23:17,498 --> 00:23:19,013
What do you mean by that, sir?

358
00:23:19,100 --> 00:23:20,608
The child Harry's vanished.

359
00:23:20,694 --> 00:23:23,319
The terms of our agreement
gave me the right.

360
00:23:23,389 --> 00:23:25,596
He's undoubtedly with his mother.
- And where's the mother?

361
00:23:25,663 --> 00:23:28,217
Someplace in the woods,
I should think.

362
00:23:28,803 --> 00:23:30,022
In the woods?

363
00:23:31,202 --> 00:23:32,303
Woods, yes.

364
00:23:33,213 --> 00:23:35,519
At least, I think that's where she is.

365
00:23:36,111 --> 00:23:37,913
She's gathering mushrooms.

366
00:23:37,998 --> 00:23:39,420
Where is the boy?

367
00:23:40,604 --> 00:23:43,221
That, you must ask
his mother, I'm afraid.

368
00:23:44,698 --> 00:23:46,822
You helped them to escape, of course.

369
00:23:46,873 --> 00:23:48,198
Sir, how dare you address my wife

370
00:23:48,249 --> 00:23:49,532
in that tone of voice!
- Do you think I'm so easily fooled?

371
00:23:49,583 --> 00:23:51,208
Mr. Legree!
- Let me tell you this...

372
00:23:51,403 --> 00:23:53,278
I give you my word of honor, sir.

373
00:23:53,329 --> 00:23:55,309
I have no idea where those two have gone.

374
00:23:55,364 --> 00:23:56,708
I'm not impressed.

375
00:23:57,403 --> 00:23:59,563
What about horses, have you horses ready?

376
00:23:59,633 --> 00:24:02,008
We'll be glad to arrange
for horses, Mr. Legree.

377
00:24:02,059 --> 00:24:02,601
Thank you.

378
00:24:02,652 --> 00:24:04,255
And you want the
horses saddled for you

379
00:24:04,306 --> 00:24:06,008
right after you finish dinner?

380
00:24:06,059 --> 00:24:08,016
No, thanks, before dinner.

381
00:24:08,102 --> 00:24:10,098
If that man ever comes
into my house again...

382
00:24:10,149 --> 00:24:12,518
Give him the oldest,
slowest ones we have.

383
00:24:13,208 --> 00:24:14,809
Nice, slow ones.

384
00:24:33,099 --> 00:24:34,809
Which way we go now?

385
00:24:34,904 --> 00:24:37,216
That's a better road,
but this one's shorter.

386
00:24:37,302 --> 00:24:38,615
You go that way!

387
00:24:42,095 --> 00:24:43,717
Here, take us across.

388
00:24:44,103 --> 00:24:45,273
We've got to cross right away.

389
00:24:45,324 --> 00:24:47,415
Impossible, the ferry's not running.

390
00:24:47,708 --> 00:24:49,704
Well, isn't there some other boat then?

391
00:24:49,755 --> 00:24:51,310
The river's full of ice.

392
00:24:52,103 --> 00:24:54,023
You can't get across.

393
00:24:55,100 --> 00:24:56,318
But I must.

394
00:24:57,494 --> 00:24:58,724
You're mad!

395
00:24:58,800 --> 00:25:01,904
Stay here, you can't get across there!

396
00:25:26,397 --> 00:25:28,225
Seen anybody come by here?

397
00:25:28,303 --> 00:25:29,267
Nobody.

398
00:25:29,327 --> 00:25:30,624
What's this wagon here?

399
00:25:30,709 --> 00:25:32,811
Must've come unhitched somewhere.

400
00:26:13,299 --> 00:26:14,427
Are you out of your mind?

401
00:26:14,478 --> 00:26:15,908
She's not my property.

402
00:26:15,959 --> 00:26:17,510
But they're getting away.

403
00:26:17,561 --> 00:26:19,287
If you kill her it'll cost me $1,000,

404
00:26:19,338 --> 00:26:20,809
and you'll be a murderer.

405
00:26:20,860 --> 00:26:22,595
Yes, but, Mr. Legree, I thought...

406
00:26:22,646 --> 00:26:24,408
Think with what, you idiot?

407
00:26:26,595 --> 00:26:29,510
Come on, your black brothers
are there waiting for you.

408
00:26:32,201 --> 00:26:35,205
If you're black, nothing
you do for him is right.

409
00:27:01,892 --> 00:27:02,907
Hold it.

410
00:27:03,790 --> 00:27:06,210
He's gonna go right on
hitting you if you don't talk.

411
00:27:06,261 --> 00:27:09,507
You better tell me where that
no-good brother of yours is.

412
00:27:10,905 --> 00:27:12,316
Hello, Morrison.

413
00:27:13,600 --> 00:27:16,350
I've come to fetch Harris.
You can put him in there.

414
00:27:16,401 --> 00:27:18,315
No, I can't, he's run away.

415
00:27:18,411 --> 00:27:19,823
You must be joking!

416
00:27:19,899 --> 00:27:21,213
I wish I was.

417
00:27:21,307 --> 00:27:22,713
I've got his sister there, though.

418
00:27:22,768 --> 00:27:25,518
I'll beat it out of her where he is.
- His sister?

419
00:27:25,705 --> 00:27:28,615
And I had my troubles today
with his wife and son.

420
00:27:29,396 --> 00:27:32,412
I might just as well see what the rest
of the family looks like.

421
00:27:41,808 --> 00:27:43,902
She's a pretty one.
What's her name?

422
00:27:43,953 --> 00:27:45,004
Casey.

423
00:27:45,698 --> 00:27:47,316
Pretty name, Casey.

424
00:27:48,602 --> 00:27:51,625
How'd you like to come with
me in place of your brother?

425
00:27:52,609 --> 00:27:53,906
Know how to cook?

426
00:27:56,098 --> 00:27:57,817
Good, I'll take her with me.

427
00:28:00,410 --> 00:28:03,356
You got the best of our deal, Morrison.
You're getting off easy.

428
00:28:03,407 --> 00:28:06,106
Well, what's a few
dollars between old friends?

429
00:28:06,598 --> 00:28:08,012
Have a good trip.

430
00:29:00,403 --> 00:29:02,512
Get out, get out, come on.

431
00:29:02,598 --> 00:29:05,006
All right, get in line.

432
00:29:05,192 --> 00:29:07,317
Come on, old man.
You, too.

433
00:29:17,003 --> 00:29:18,019
Come.

434
00:29:21,604 --> 00:29:22,924
Go on, gal.

435
00:29:23,807 --> 00:29:25,205
Get going down there.

436
00:29:25,260 --> 00:29:26,995
Go on!
- Poor Casey.

437
00:29:27,046 --> 00:29:28,916
Shut your mouth, go on.

438
00:29:33,495 --> 00:29:35,101
Good day, Mr. Legree.

439
00:29:43,509 --> 00:29:46,118
Come on, get a move on.

440
00:29:47,016 --> 00:29:48,633
Boat won't wait for you.

441
00:29:49,102 --> 00:29:50,587
Captain, nearly ready, sir.

442
00:29:50,638 --> 00:29:53,016
Take the lap first.
We'll hit the currents on our way.

443
00:29:53,088 --> 00:29:54,610
Aye aye, sir.
- Carry on.

444
00:30:00,898 --> 00:30:03,508
Hurry up with that loading, there!

445
00:30:05,900 --> 00:30:08,102
Look out for the lambs there.

446
00:30:12,603 --> 00:30:14,813
Come on, old man, stop gawking.

447
00:30:14,900 --> 00:30:16,212
Get a move on.

448
00:30:16,501 --> 00:30:19,025
Why do they put all those
men in chains, father?

449
00:30:19,076 --> 00:30:20,409
Are they criminals?

450
00:30:21,306 --> 00:30:22,814
No, it's not that.

451
00:30:23,212 --> 00:30:25,923
They're slaves and their
owners have chained them.

452
00:30:26,302 --> 00:30:28,224
But why must they be chained?

453
00:30:28,701 --> 00:30:31,617
Well, because some owners
are wicked and cruel.

454
00:30:32,802 --> 00:30:33,912
Come, come.

455
00:30:36,499 --> 00:30:38,609
Hurry up, keep moving.

456
00:30:38,798 --> 00:30:41,426
Don't fall asleep there,
you can sleep later.

457
00:30:41,710 --> 00:30:43,818
Go on, move, hurry up!

458
00:30:44,200 --> 00:30:45,310
Get in there.

459
00:31:10,403 --> 00:31:12,208
How do you like it here?

460
00:31:13,112 --> 00:31:14,216
Here.

461
00:31:14,802 --> 00:31:17,509
Actually, I bought these
things for Lucinda.

462
00:31:17,599 --> 00:31:19,659
She's the singer in my hotel,

463
00:31:19,710 --> 00:31:21,109
but you're much younger and prettier.

464
00:31:21,160 --> 00:31:22,985
There, choose what you like.

465
00:31:23,707 --> 00:31:25,109
It's all yours.

466
00:31:26,496 --> 00:31:28,097
Take a look in the mirror.

467
00:31:31,402 --> 00:31:32,912
Here's something else.

468
00:31:33,916 --> 00:31:35,211
Wanna smell it?

469
00:31:35,398 --> 00:31:36,812
How do you like it?

470
00:31:41,604 --> 00:31:43,213
Smells good, huh?

471
00:31:46,999 --> 00:31:50,713
If you like, I'll make
a real lady out of you.

472
00:31:52,696 --> 00:31:55,006
How can you make a real lady out of me?

473
00:31:55,104 --> 00:31:56,519
I'm a negress.

474
00:31:57,903 --> 00:31:59,409
Leave that to me.

475
00:31:59,589 --> 00:32:03,000
What I say decides who's
a nigger and who isn't.

476
00:32:25,600 --> 00:32:28,217
You, sit over there where you belong.

477
00:32:29,401 --> 00:32:31,345
This man gave you
money for clothes for us.

478
00:32:31,396 --> 00:32:32,756
What'd you do, drink it?

479
00:32:32,807 --> 00:32:35,612
Mr. Legree got all kind
of clothes on the plantation

480
00:32:35,663 --> 00:32:37,612
off all the slaves that died.

481
00:32:37,663 --> 00:32:39,815
Get out, what is this a funeral?

482
00:32:40,500 --> 00:32:43,120
What do you think they're all
saying about you up there?

483
00:32:43,300 --> 00:32:45,026
If you behave yourselves,
you'll be treated well,

484
00:32:45,077 --> 00:32:46,703
and, if not, look out.

485
00:32:46,800 --> 00:32:48,716
Do we understand each other?

486
00:32:48,802 --> 00:32:49,912
Well, answer.

487
00:32:49,963 --> 00:32:51,506
Yes, sir.
- All right.

488
00:32:52,302 --> 00:32:54,160
Now, let's hear you sing a song.

489
00:32:54,211 --> 00:32:55,271
Sing whatever you want to,

490
00:32:55,322 --> 00:32:57,326
sing one of those spirituals.

491
00:32:57,377 --> 00:32:58,412
All right?

492
00:32:58,487 --> 00:32:59,810
Why don't you sing?

493
00:33:00,998 --> 00:33:02,404
Sing, I said.

494
00:34:21,695 --> 00:34:22,795
Excuse me.

495
00:35:02,901 --> 00:35:04,713
Did y'all like it, Miss?

496
00:35:04,809 --> 00:35:07,120
Yes, your singing was very beautiful.

497
00:35:07,306 --> 00:35:09,112
Why must you wear these?

498
00:35:09,308 --> 00:35:11,104
So we don't run away.

499
00:35:11,206 --> 00:35:12,573
Well, I think it's awful.

500
00:35:12,637 --> 00:35:14,713
Oh, that's how things is, child.

501
00:35:14,901 --> 00:35:16,886
You better go now, before
you get some trouble

502
00:35:16,937 --> 00:35:18,146
for coming down here.

503
00:35:18,197 --> 00:35:19,812
Will you let me visit you again?

504
00:35:19,863 --> 00:35:21,414
If your mother says you can.

505
00:35:21,492 --> 00:35:24,422
Oh, she's at home, but my
father lets me do anything.

506
00:35:24,498 --> 00:35:25,625
Does he?

507
00:35:26,394 --> 00:35:27,938
Oh, I'm glad you came, Father.

508
00:35:27,989 --> 00:35:29,918
Please, break off these chains.

509
00:35:30,004 --> 00:35:33,012
I can't do that, dear,
I'm not their owner.

510
00:35:33,097 --> 00:35:34,207
Who is?

511
00:35:34,308 --> 00:35:36,406
First, my Lord, then Mr. Legree.

512
00:35:36,492 --> 00:35:38,012
Well, I'll talk with the Lord.

513
00:35:38,090 --> 00:35:40,701
And my father will speak
to Mr. Legree.

514
00:35:45,701 --> 00:35:47,115
My name's Evangeline.

515
00:35:47,203 --> 00:35:48,708
But they all call me Eva.

516
00:35:48,775 --> 00:35:50,935
And I'm Thomas, but
they calls me Uncle Tom.

517
00:35:50,998 --> 00:35:53,107
You must call me Uncle Tom, too.

518
00:35:53,170 --> 00:35:54,349
All right, Uncle Tom.

519
00:35:54,400 --> 00:35:57,310
I'm going, but I'll see you
again tomorrow. Bye.

520
00:35:57,607 --> 00:35:58,928
Good day.

521
00:36:06,806 --> 00:36:08,432
Excuse me, sir.

522
00:36:08,611 --> 00:36:11,216
Do you own those people downstairs?

523
00:36:11,897 --> 00:36:13,732
I own them, yes.

524
00:36:14,099 --> 00:36:15,936
Why must you eat alone?

525
00:36:16,396 --> 00:36:17,908
I prefer to eat alone.

526
00:36:17,978 --> 00:36:19,408
It gives me time to...

527
00:36:19,478 --> 00:36:22,412
I must ask you to forgive her
for disturbing you, sir, but...

